5.2 The 5-Layer Prompt Architecture
Every Groq call is built from 5 layers injected in this exact order. Never skip a layer.

Layer	Content	Purpose
1 — Role	You are BRAUDLE, a patient personal tutor. You teach step by step. You never summarise. You ask one check question after each explanation. You never skip a wrong answer.	Defines AI identity and core behaviour
2 — Student	Level: {level}. Goal: {goal}. Learning style: {style}. Weak topics: {weakTopics}. Subjects: {subjects}.	Personalises every single response
3 — Chunk	Here is the section to teach right now: {chunkText}. Teach in 3-5 clear points using language appropriate for {level} level. End with one comprehension question.	Grounds AI in actual document content
4 — History	Full messages[] array from Conversation collection injected here in order	Gives AI memory of entire session
5 — Rules	If answer is wrong: identify the specific misconception. Correct it clearly. Ask a simpler follow-up. Never be discouraging. Never skip wrong answers.	Controls evaluation and correction behaviour

// src/utils/promptBuilder.ts
export function buildTeachPrompt(
  chunk:      string,
  profile:    StudentProfile,
  isBreakdown = false
): string {
  const levelInstructions = {
    beginner:     'Use simple everyday language. Define every technical term. Use real world analogies.',
    intermediate: 'Use standard academic language. Technical terms with brief context.',
    advanced:     'Use precise technical terminology. Assume strong prior knowledge. Go deeper than surface.',
  }[profile.level];

  const goalContext = profile.goal === 'scholarship'
    ? 'This student is working toward a scholarship. Be thorough and encouraging.'
    : '';

  const breakdownInstruction = isBreakdown
    ? 'The student is confused. Use a DIFFERENT approach than before. Try: simpler analogy, step-by-step logic, real world example. Do not move on until they confirm they understand.'
    : 'Teach in 3-5 clear points. End with exactly one comprehension question.';

  return `You are BRAUDLE, a patient personal tutor.
  You teach step by step. You never summarise.
  ${levelInstructions}
  ${goalContext}
  SECTION TO TEACH: ${chunk}
  INSTRUCTION: ${breakdownInstruction}`,
}
 
💾  SECTION 6: CACHING STRATEGY
Redis caching — what to cache, keys, TTLs, and how it saves API calls

6.1 Why Caching Is Critical
If 200 students from the same foundation all study the same biology PDF at beginner level, the AI explanation for chunk 0 is essentially identical for all 200. Without caching: 200 Groq API calls. With caching: 1 Groq call served 199 times for free.

IMPACT	With a foundation of 200 students on the same document, caching reduces Groq API calls by roughly 70%. This keeps BRAUDLE well within the free tier even at significant scale.

6.2 Complete Cache Reference
What to Cache	Redis Key Pattern	TTL	Why This TTL
Chunk explanation	teach:{docId}:{chunkIdx}:{level}	24 hours	Same doc+level = same explanation. Expires daily to allow updates.
Quiz questions	quiz:{documentId}	48 hours	Same doc = same quiz. Reused across all students studying it.
Chunk embeddings	embed:{docId}:{chunkIdx}	7 days	Embeddings never change for static content.
Session summary	summary:{sessionId}	7 days	Student may revisit their summary — keep it fast.
Student profile	profile:{userId}	10 minutes	Read on every session start — cache cuts DB load.
Rate limit counter	rl:{userId}:{feature}:{window}	Varies	In-memory rate check — faster than DB query.
Document status	doc:status:{documentId}	1 hour	Frontend polls for processing status — cache reduces DB reads.

6.3 Cache Implementation Pattern
// src/utils/cache.ts
import { redis } from '../config/redis';

export async function getCached<T>(key: string): Promise<T | null> {
  const val = await redis.get(key);
  return val ? JSON.parse(val) : null;
}

export async function setCached(key: string, value: any, ttlSeconds: number): Promise<void> {
  await redis.setex(key, ttlSeconds, JSON.stringify(value));
}

// Usage in session controller
const cacheKey = `teach:${documentId}:${chunkIndex}:${profile.level}`;
const cached   = await getCached<string>(cacheKey);

if (cached) {
  // Serve from cache — zero Groq cost
  return res.json({ explanation: cached, fromCache: true });
}

// Cache miss — call Groq
const explanation = await callGroq(messages, GROQ_MODELS.smart);
await setCached(cacheKey, explanation, 86400);  // 24 hours
return res.json({ explanation, fromCache: false });

6.4 What NOT to Cache
Never Cache This	Why
Student answer evaluations	Every student answer is unique — caching would give wrong results
Misconception corrections	Specific to each student's exact wrong answer — never reusable
Conversation history responses	Depend on everything said in session — always unique
Tutor flag decisions	Context-dependent — same answer may need flagging in some sessions not others
 
